{{Infobox rugby league international tournament | year = 1986 | title = Pacific Cup | image = | imagesize = | alt = | finalists = 6 | country = Cook Islands | winners = New Zealand Māori | count = 3 | matches = 10 | attendance = | points = | tries = | topscorer-flag = | topscorer = | top try scorer-flag= | top try scorer = | tournaments = Pacific Cup | last = [[1977 Pacific Cup|1977]] | next = [[1988 Pacific Cup|1988]] }} The '''1986 Pacific Cup''' was the 3rd [[Pacific Cup]], a [[rugby league]] tournament held between Pacific teams. The tournament was hosted in the Cook Islands and eventually won by the [[New Zealand Māori rugby league team|New Zealand Māori]] side, who defeated [[Samoa national rugby league team|Western Samoa]] in the final.
==Background== The 1986 Pacific Cup was the first to be held after the cancellation of the planned 1979 version. Only the New Zealand Māori side returned from the first two editions, as this Pacific Cup had a more Pacific Island focus than the first two which included Papua New Guinea (who now had Test status) and Australian lower grade sides.<ref name=book/>
==Squads== *The Cook Islands included [[John Whittaker (rugby league)|John Whittaker]], [[George Lajpold]] and [[Riki Cowan]]. *Coached by [[Richard Bolton (rugby league)|Richard Bolton]], the New Zealand Māori squad included [[Gary Mercer]], [[Dave Watson (rugby league)|Dave Watson]], [[Adrian Shelford]], [[Mark Woods (rugby league)|Mark Woods]], [[Anthony Murray (rugby league)|Anthony Murray]], captain [[Sam Stewart (rugby league)|Sam Stewart]], [[Mark Horo]], [[Tawera Nikau]] and [[Mike Kuiti]]. [[Hugh McGahan]], [[Ron O'Regan]], [[Owen Wright]], Tracey McGregor, [[Andrew Vincent]] and [[Brendon Tuuta]] all pulled out of the side due to injury or professional club commitments.<ref name=book>{{cite book | last =John Coffey, Bernie Wood | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = 100 years: Māori rugby league, 1908-2008 | publisher =Huia Publishers | year = 2008 | location = | pages = 224–226 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nklWo8vw-iIC&printsec=frontcover | doi = | id = | isbn =978-1-86969-331-2}}</ref> The Māori side played a warm up game before the competition began, defeating [[Waikato rugby league team|Waikato]] 52-32. It was the first time in over two decades that the Māori side was comprised completely of Māori players, as the side had previously also picked Polynesian players.<ref name=book/> *Tokelau included [[Sam Panapa]]. The rest of the squad was selected entirely from domestic players, chosen from a population of just over 1000.<ref name=book/> *Tonga included [[John Fifita]], [[George Mann (rugby league)|George Mann]], [[Dick Uluave]] and [[Robert Fonua]]. *Western Samoa included [[Paddy Tuimavave]], [[Esene Faimalo]], Robert Moimoi, Mike Kerrigan, Richard Setu and [[Paul Okesene]].<ref name=cxiii>Coffey, John. ''Canterbury XIII'', Christchurch, 1987.</ref>
===Team of the Tournament=== The 1986 Pacific Cup Tournament team was named at the end of the tournament and included: George Huriwai (Māori), [[Gary Mercer]] (Māori), Ampelea Aiolupotea (Samoa), Robert Fonua (Tonga), Alimone Liavaa (Tonga), [[Paddy Tuimavave]] (Samoa), [[Sam Panapa]] (Tokelau), Neville Ramsay (Māori), Dave Sefuiva (Samoa), [[Adrian Shelford]] (Māori), Simona Foua (Tokelau), Mick Curran (Tonga), Simona Foua (Samoa), [[Sam Stewart (rugby league)|Sam Stewart]] (Māori), [[John Fifita]] (Tonga), Lorne Greene (Māori) and [[Dick Uluave]] (Tonga).<ref name=book/>
