{{Infobox company | name = Behaviour Interactive Inc. | logo = Behaviour Interactive logo.svg | former_name = {{Unbulleted list|Megatoon Entertainment Group Inc. {{small|(1992–1998)}}|Behaviour Interactive Inc. {{small|(1998–2000)}}|Artificial Mind & Movement Inc. {{small|(2000–2010)}}}} | type = [[Privately held company|Private]] | industry = [[Video game industry]] | fate = | founded = {{Start date and age|1992|09|21}} in [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]], Canada | founder = Rémi Racine | defunct = <!-- {{end date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | hq_location_city = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]] | hq_location_country = [[Canada]] | area_served = Worldwide | key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Rémi Racine {{small|([[President (corporate title)|President]])}}|Stephen Mulrooney {{small|([[Chief technology officer|CTO]])}}|Roland Ribotti {{small|([[Chief financial officer|CFO]])}}}} | products = {{Unbulleted list|''[[Wet (video game)|Wet]]''|''[[Scaler (video game)|Scaler]]''|''[[Indiana Jones and the Staff of Kings]]''|''[[Happy Feet (video game)|Happy Feet]]''|''[[Fallout Shelter]]''}} | num_employees = 475 | num_employees_year = 2018<ref>https://www.bhvr.com/fr/behaviour-interactif-renforce-sa-presence-mondiale-grace-a-un-partenariat-strategique-avec-gaea-interactive-entertainment/</ref> | website = {{URL|bhvr.com}} }}
'''Behaviour Interactive Inc.''' ({{lang-fr|Behaviour Intéractif Inc.}}, stylized as '''bE HAVIOUR''') is a Canadian video game development studio specializing in the production of 2D and 3D action/adventure games for [[home video game console]]s, [[handheld game console]]s and [[personal computer]]s.
==History== The company was founded in 1992 in [[Quebec City]] by Rémi Racine as Megatoon Entertainment Group.<ref name=JoystiqRebrands /><ref name=GamasutraJobs>{{cite web|title=Gamasutra Jobs - Behaviour Interactive|url=http://jobs.gamasutra.com/company/behaviour-interactive-128823|publisher=Gamasutra|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref> Two years later, Racine co-founded a Montreal-based Multimedia Interactive (MMI) to develop interactive entertainment software for CD-ROM.<ref name=BehaviourHistory>{{cite web|title=Our History |url=http://www.bhvr.com/about-us/our-history/ |publisher=Behaviour Interactive inc. |accessdate=September 7, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140901170653/http://www.bhvr.com/about-us/our-history/ |archivedate=September 1, 2014 |df= }}</ref> Both companies were sold to Malofilm Communications in 1996, and a year later, they were merged into Behaviour Interactive.<ref name=BehaviourHistory /> In 1999, Racine and some investors bought the studio back, but they had to rename it, changing the name in 2000 to Artificial Mind & Movement Inc. (A2M).<ref name=JoystiqRebrands /><ref name=BehaviourHistory /> In November 2008, the company acquired [[Santiago]]-based [[Behaviour Santiago|Wanako Games]] from [[Activision Blizzard]],<ref>{{cite press release|author1=A2M|title=A2M Acquires Chilean Developer Wanako Games|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aAvba_nfh3fs|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=September 7, 2014|date=November 20, 2008}}</ref> which was the first and largest South American game studio.<ref name=BehaviourHistory /> By 2010, the studio's name was reverted to Behaviour Interactive, partly due to increased production of original titles and thus stronger presence in the gaming community, partly due to the availability of the original name, and partly due to [[Ass to mouth|one particular obscene interpretation]] of the initialism "A2M".<ref name=JoystiqRebrands>{{cite web|last1=Grant|first1=Christopher|title=Artificial Mind and Movement rebrands; (re)introducing Behaviour Interactive|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2010/11/08/artificial-mind-and-movement-rebrands-re-introducing-behaviour/|publisher=Joystiq|accessdate=September 7, 2014|date=November 8, 2010}}</ref>
