The '''Komazawa Hockey Field''' was a venue constructed in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] for the [[Field hockey at the 1964 Summer Olympics|field hockey]] competitions of [[1964 Summer Olympics]]. Although there were three hockey fields, it marked the first time the [[field hockey]] was played in one single venue for the [[Summer Olympics]] since the [[Field hockey at the 1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Games]].
==Hockey Field 1== The first hockey field seated 2056 and had a playing field measuring {{convert|104.4|m|yd|0|abbr=off}} long by {{convert|66|m|yd|abbr=off}} wide. It also featured an electronic scoreboard. Construction occurred between December 1962 and June 1964.
==Hockey Field 2== The second hockey field seated 3432 with 1542 tempoarary seats and had a playing field measuring {{convert|115|m|yd|abbr=off}} long by {{convert|80|m|yd|abbr=off}} wide. It also featured an electronic scoreboard. Construction occurred between December 1962 and June 1964.
==Hockey Field 3== The third hockey field seated 2343 and had a playing field measuring {{convert|9900|m2|yd2|abbr=off}}. Construction occurred between December 1962 and September 1964.
==References== *[https://web.archive.org/web/20100707162648/http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1964/or1964v1pt1.pdf 1964 Summer Olympics official report.] Volume 1. Part 1. pp.&nbsp;126–7.
