{{Infobox person |image = File:Getting acquainted.jpg |image_size = 250px |caption = Clockwise from top: Phyllis Allen, [[Mack Swain]], [[Charles Chaplin]], and [[Mabel Normand]] in ''[[Getting Acquainted]]'' (1914) |birth_date = {{birth date|1861|11|25}} |birth_place = [[Staten Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S. |death_date = {{death date and age|1938|3|26|1861|11|25}} |death_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S. |occupation = Actress, comedian, [[vaudevillian]] |years_active = 1913–1923 }}
'''Phyllis Allen''' (November 25, 1861 – March 26, 1938) was an [[United States|American]] [[vaudeville]] and [[silent film|silent screen]] [[comedian]] who worked with [[Charles Chaplin]], [[Mabel Normand]], [[Roscoe "Fatty" Arbuckle]], and [[Mack Sennett]] during a film career spanning 74 movies in the decade between 1913 and 1923. Due to her imposing demeanour and perennially haughty expression, she was quite similar in appearance to fellow screen comedian [[Marie Dressler]].
